Let's take each of these effects in turn. 
First, is the \empleffect, which is in three parts:
the direct emplacement effect = 0\%; 
the embodied energy effect, which is positive (+1.4\%), 
due to the higher embodied energy (+6,000MJ) 
stemming from the electric battery in the hybrid EV car; 
and the maintenance and disposal effect (-1.0\%), 
which is low and negative  
because of the slightly lower maintenance and disposal costs
in the hybrid EV car. 
Second, is the \subeffect, 
which splits into two components 
at the original income level. 
The direct substitution effect yields +2.9\% value,
which is expected, as the new fuel efficiency (42 mpg) 
is much higher than the baseline car (25 mpg), 
leading to a preference to switch more spending to more driving. 
In other words, with no other changes, 
the more fuel efficient car increases the amount of miles driven by 2.9\%. 
Conversely, the indirect substitution effect yields a value of -0.3\%, 
being slightly negative as the increased fuel use 
and miles driven in the direct substitution effect 
means that less is spent on other goods.  

Third, is the \inceffect, 
where the car 
user sees an increase in their ‘effective’ income
due to a net saving in outgoings associated with the car purchase and use, 
this effect also splits into two. 
One is the direct income effect (+5.3\%), 
which is positive and non-zero as the car user allocates some
of the additional income to driving further still. 
The indirect income effect is also positive (+7.8\%), 
due to higher spend on other sectors. 
So, the additional ``effective'' income 
($\rasub{N} = 712$ \$/year) 
translates into direct and indirect income effects at the micro-level. 
Last, is the macroeconomic 
\prodeffect (+8.2\%), 
due to the larger economy that now exists, 
so the additional money spent in the economy 
has a positive rebound multiplier effect.


