Taking each of the four rebound effects in turn, 
the first is the \empleffect = -0.3\%. 
It's three parts are the direct emplacement effect = 0\%; 
the embodied energy effect (-0.3\%) which is negative, 
as although the LED lamp has higher embodied energy (+4.3MJ),
it also has a much longer lifetime, 
meaning the LED embodied energy rate (0.65MJ/year) 
is lower than for the incandescent lamp (1.23MJ/year); and
the maintenance and disposal effect is zero (0\%),
because of there is no difference in the negligible costs 
(\$0.001) assumed for the two lamps. 
Second, is the \subeffect at the original income level, 
which is split into two parts. 
The direct substitution effect yields +17.4\% value, 
due to the much higher LED lamp efficacy (82Lm/W versus 9Lm/W), 
which translates to increasing the average lamp use 
from 3 hours/day to 3 hour 30 mins per day. 
Due to the highly positive direct effect, 
the indirect substitution effect 
(remember, this is at the original income level)
must be negative and it is (-12.7\%),
as the increased lighting use from the direct substitution 
effect means that less is spent on other goods. 

Third is the \subeffect, split into two ‘income’ effects, 
where the electric lamp user respends their higher ‘effective’ income 
%(Ndot_hat 
($\rasub{N} = 15$ \$/year) which results from a net saving in outgoings
associated with the eletric lamp purchase and use.
The direct income effect (+0.02\%), 
which is positive as the lamp user allocates 
some of the additional income to increased lighting, 
but is very small. 
The indirect income effect is highly positive (+24.7\%),
due to the preference for higher spend on other goods.
So, the additional ‘effective’ income. 
Finally, the macroeconomic macroeconomic 
\prodeffect (+24.7\%) is large and positive, 
as the additional consumption of goods in the economy 
has a positive rebound multiplier effect.



